  "body": "Using 0.12\n\nvar Sample = React.createClass({\n  someFunc: function(e) {\n    // not there\n    console.log(e.layerY, e.layerX, e.x, e.y, e.movementX, e.movementY, e.offsetX, offsetY);\n    // are there\n    console.log(e.nativeEvent.layerY, e.nativeEvent.layerX, e.nativeEvent.x, e.nativeEvent.y, e.nativeEvent.movementX, e.nativeEvent.movementY, e.nativeEvent.offsetX, e.nativeEvent.offsetY)\n  }\n  render: function() {\n    return (\n      <div onMouseMove={this.someFunc}>\n      </div>\n    );\n  }\n});\n\nSo looking at this, it might be that react is only taking the more standard fields across? In Chrome layerY give me the position from the top of the element the event is over. I can get it using only the react event like so\n\ne.clientY - e.currentTarget.getBoundingClientRect().top\n\nSo I'm not sure if this needs to be fixed or not, any thoughts?\n\nCheers,\nLuke\n",
